    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Japan, What's on the Plate Is Culture</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Naoko Tsujimoto letter defends allowing Japan to hunt certain number of whales to maintain culinary culture of eating whale meat (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Japan, Feasting on Whale, Sniffs at 'Culinary Imperialism' of U.S.'' (front page, Aug. 10):</p>
        <p>Cuisine is culture. The International Whaling Commission should allow Japan to hunt a certain number of whales, not for scientific purposes but for maintaining the tradition of eating whales, which must be preserved as part of Japanese culinary culture.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Japan, Feasting on Whale, Sniffs at 'Culinary Imperialism' of U.S.'' (front page, Aug. 10):</p>
        <p>Cuisine is culture. The International Whaling Commission should allow Japan to hunt a certain number of whales, not for scientific purposes but for maintaining the tradition of eating whales, which must be preserved as part of Japanese culinary culture.</p>
        <p>Many Westerners might perceive it as a brutal destruction of nature, but no country, including the United States, has the right to put an end to Japanese tradition.</p>
        <p>What will be left in Japan to identify ourselves after the homogenization (or Americanization) of culture?</p>
        <p>NAOKO TSUJIMOTO  Brooklyn, Aug. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
